WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.660 --> 00:00:04.460
And speaking about being a grownup in America, Abby Edwards

2
00:00:04.520 --> 00:00:06.980
is a senior at Butler, and she has already completed

3
00:00:07.020 --> 00:00:09.260
more college than most of us in the room through

4
00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:14.100
Wright State. So please welcome Abby Edwards and

5
00:00:14.180 --> 00:00:17.400
her dog, Kathy with a K, to the stage

6
00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:41.760
Keep walking straight. Okay. Right here where I'm standing.

7
00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:47.000
Okay. So you stand right there. Where? Okay. All right,

8
00:00:47.340 --> 00:00:49.760
so how is everybody? We're half-- We're more than halfway

9
00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:52.680
through. How we feeling? You still excited to be here?

10
00:00:53.470 --> 00:00:57.760
Yeah. Well, I'm still excited to be here

11
00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:04.460
because my name, as Sam very eloquently said,

12
00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:08.200
is Abby Edwards, and I am here today to share

13
00:01:08.240 --> 00:01:11.880
with you the impact that self-advocacy can have on your

14
00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:16.760
life. Now, when most people think of self-advocacy,

15
00:01:17.540 --> 00:01:20.400
they think that it's just a way to get something

16
00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:25.260
done. When I thought of self-advocacy, I envisioned something

17
00:01:25.280 --> 00:01:30.230
dramatic, like a petition, like someone in Washington. I didn't

18
00:01:30.320 --> 00:01:34.020
know that self-advocacy could be as simple as sending an

19
00:01:34.100 --> 00:01:38.440
email. It wasn't until I was asked to speak about

20
00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:42.860
it that I realized what self-advocacy really is, a choice

21
00:01:42.980 --> 00:01:46.920
to take control of your life. Now, that's all well

22
00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:50.460
and good. If it's so simple, why haven't we all

23
00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:54.860
done it? Maybe it's because we don't feel like it's

24
00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:58.820
our choice to make. We live in a world that

25
00:01:58.860 --> 00:02:03.080
is constantly changing. New technology and trends come out all

26
00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:05.670
the time, and it can give us the impression that

27
00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:08.440
we don't really have a say in what goes on

28
00:02:08.479 --> 00:02:12.480
in the world around us. I can personally relate to

29
00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:15.840
feeling out of control. Around four and a half years

30
00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:18.300
ago, I was at a point in my life where

31
00:02:18.360 --> 00:02:20.660
I felt like I had no say over what happened

32
00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:24.170
to me. At this point, I had just lost the

33
00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:27.840
remainder of my vision, had just had major back surgery,

34
00:02:28.340 --> 00:02:30.840
and was going through a second round of IV treatment

35
00:02:30.960 --> 00:02:35.180
for osteoporosis. This was a time in my life where

36
00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:37.420
I felt like everything had been taken out of my

37
00:02:37.480 --> 00:02:41.580
hands. Just before my freshman year of high school, I

38
00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:44.410
started exploring the role that technology could have in my

39
00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:48.760
life. I began to utilize things like email to communicate

40
00:02:48.780 --> 00:02:52.920
with my teachers and to complete assignments. At some point

41
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.080
that year, I became aware of all the opportunities that

42
00:02:56.120 --> 00:02:58.440
had been opened up to me, and I made the

43
00:02:58.540 --> 00:03:02.170
choice to embrace all that life had to offer. With

44
00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:06.420
renewed confidence, I communicated with admissions staff at Wright State,

45
00:03:06.740 --> 00:03:10.260
and then my sophomore year, with my first ever college

46
00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:15.080
professors. As my confidence continued to grow, I decided to

47
00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:18.310
apply for a guide dog. I was approved by Guiding

48
00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:21.920
Eyes for the Blind and spent a life-changing summer training

49
00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:25.790
with my guide dog, Kathy, in New York. I got

50
00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:28.590
more than just a dog that summer, though. I got

51
00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:31.720
even more confidence because now I was able to not

52
00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:36.780
just talk confidently, but also to walk confidently. I carried

53
00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:39.549
this confidence into my junior year, and when I was

54
00:03:39.640 --> 00:03:42.200
having trouble in one of my psychology classes at Wright

55
00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:45.080
State, I was able to confidently speak with the dean

56
00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:49.360
of the department to resolve my problem. Everyone around me

57
00:03:49.400 --> 00:03:52.880
noticed how confident I felt, so my school district nominated

58
00:03:52.940 --> 00:03:56.730
me for a National Self-Advocacy Award. As a result of

59
00:03:56.760 --> 00:03:59.140
receiving this award, I was able to be a guest

60
00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:02.800
on a radio show, a local newscast, and had several

61
00:04:02.840 --> 00:04:07.630
opportunities to speak for different civic groups. Last summer, as

62
00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:10.920
a result of advocating for myself, I attended an independent

63
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.710
living program that taught me invaluable skills like cooking,

64
00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:20.200
cleaning, things that will last me a lifetime. Looking back,

65
00:04:20.340 --> 00:04:22.780
I realized that it was my choice to take control

66
00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:25.500
of my life those four and a half years ago

67
00:04:25.520 --> 00:04:29.000
that has led me to where I am today. Now,

68
00:04:29.060 --> 00:04:31.700
thus far, you've been sitting back listening to my story

69
00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:34.720
thinking, "Gosh, this is nice. I don't have to do

70
00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:38.200
anything." So this is where I would like to extend

71
00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:41.640
a challenge to everyone here today to come up with

72
00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:44.180
at least one thing that you would like to see

73
00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:48.940
change in your life. Ask yourself, "What can I do

74
00:04:49.060 --> 00:04:53.990
to accomplish this?" Then realize that you have the power

75
00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:57.300
to make that goal a reality. You will find out,

76
00:04:57.620 --> 00:05:00.760
as I once did, that once you start advocating for

77
00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:04.260
yourself, it gets easier and easier to accomplish bigger and

78
00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:09.140
bigger goals. Consider the impact that simply deciding to take

79
00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:11.760
control of your life could have on you and those

80
00:05:11.820 --> 00:05:15.480
around you. And don't just think of self-advocacy as a

81
00:05:15.520 --> 00:05:18.180
way to get things done. Think of it as a

82
00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:21.340
state of mind, one that will take you as far

83
00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:23.740
as you can imagine. Thank you.
